Here's how to set up switchable themes in .NET MAUI:

## 1. Define Resource Dictionaries for each theme

Create separate XAML resource dictionaries:

```xml
<!-- Resources/Styles/LightTheme.xaml -->
<ResourceDictionary xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
                    xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml">
    <Color x:Key="PageBackground">#FFFFFF</Color>
    <Color x:Key="TextPrimary">#1A1A1A</Color>
    <Color x:Key="AccentColor">#0078D4</Color>
</ResourceDictionary>
```

```xml
<!-- Resources/Styles/DarkTheme.xaml -->
<ResourceDictionary ...>
    <Color x:Key="PageBackground">#1E1E1E</Color>
    <Color x:Key="TextPrimary">#F0F0F0</Color>
    <Color x:Key="AccentColor">#4CC2FF</Color>
</ResourceDictionary>
```

```xml
<!-- Resources/Styles/HighContrastTheme.xaml -->
<ResourceDictionary ...>
    <Color x:Key="PageBackground">#000000</Color>
    <Color x:Key="TextPrimary">#FFFFFF</Color>
    <Color x:Key="AccentColor">#FFFF00</Color>
</ResourceDictionary>
```

## 2. Create a Theme Service

```csharp
public enum AppTheme { Light, Dark, HighContrast }

public static class ThemeService
{
    public static void SetTheme(AppTheme theme)
    {
        var mergedDictionaries = Application.Current!.Resources.MergedDictionaries;

        // Remove existing theme dictionary (keep other dictionaries like Styles.xaml)
        var existing = mergedDictionaries.FirstOrDefault(d => d.Source?.OriginalString.Contains("Theme") == true);
        if (existing != null)
            mergedDictionaries.Remove(existing);

        var themeDictionary = theme switch
        {
            AppTheme.Dark => new DarkTheme(),
            AppTheme.HighContrast => new HighContrastTheme(),
            _ => new LightTheme()
        };

        mergedDictionaries.Add(themeDictionary);

        // Persist the choice
        Preferences.Set("AppTheme", theme.ToString());
    }

    public static AppTheme GetSavedTheme()
    {
        var saved = Preferences.Get("AppTheme", nameof(AppTheme.Light));
        return Enum.Parse<AppTheme>(saved);
    }
}
```

## 3. Wire up in App.xaml.cs

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    public App()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        ThemeService.SetTheme(ThemeService.GetSavedTheme());
    }
}
```

## 4. Use `DynamicResource` in your UI

This is the key — `StaticResource` won't update at runtime:

```xml
<ContentPage BackgroundColor="{DynamicResource PageBackground}">
    <Label TextColor="{DynamicResource TextPrimary}" Text="Hello!" />
</ContentPage>
```

## 5. Settings Page

```xml
<Picker x:Name="ThemePicker" Title="Theme"
        ItemsSource="{Binding Themes}"
        SelectedIndexChanged="OnThemeChanged" />
```

```csharp
void OnThemeChanged(object sender, EventArgs e)
{
    var selected = (AppTheme)ThemePicker.SelectedIndex;
    ThemeService.SetTheme(selected);
}
```

## Key points

- **`DynamicResource`** enables live switching without restarting.
- **`Preferences`** persists the user's choice across sessions.
- Use consistent `x:Key` names across all theme dictionaries so references resolve regardless of which is active.
- You can extend this with `Style` entries (e.g., `BaseButtonStyle`) inside each theme for component-level theming.
